    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the biology and chemistry of the microbes.\n\nThe wild yeast and lactobacilli in your sourdough starter are microorganisms that feed on the sugars present in the dough. The wild yeast, typically a mixture of species, consumes sugars and produces carbon dioxide gas as a byproduct, causing the dough to rise. The lactobacilli, on the other hand, break down the starches and other complex carbohydrates into simpler sugars, which are then consumed by the wild yeast.\n\nThe enzymatic breakdown of starches into fermentable sugars is a key step in the fermentation process. Amylases, produced by the wild yeast, break down starches into maltose, a disaccharide composed of two glucose molecules. The lactobacilli then convert maltose into glucose, which is then consumed by the wild yeast.\n\nTemperature and hydration levels affect the activity of these enzymes and the growth of the microorganisms. Higher temperatures (around 25-30°C) favor the growth of the wild yeast, while lower temperatures (around 15-20°C) favor the growth of the lactobacilli. Hydration levels also impact the activity of the enzymes,",
