      "content": "The type of flour used can indeed impact the rate of gas production and the activity of the microorganisms. Rye flour, for example, contains more pentosans, a type of complex carbohydrate that is resistant to amylase breakdown. This means that the wild yeast will have to work harder to break down the starches in rye flour, resulting in a slower rate of gas production.\n\nAdditionally, rye flour contains more phenolic compounds, which can inhibit the growth of the lactobacilli. This can lead to a more yeasty flavor and a slower fermentation rate. On the other hand, all-purpose flour contains more easily digestible carbohydrates, which can lead to a faster rate of gas production and a more sour flavor.\n\nThe type of flour can also affect the pH of the dough, with rye flour producing a more acidic environment due to the higher levels of phenolic compounds. This can impact the activity of the microorganisms, with the wild yeast thriving in the acidic environment and the lactobacilli struggling to survive.\n\nTo give you a better idea, here's a rough estimate of the impact of different flour types on gas production:\n\n* All-purpose flour: 10-15% CO2 production\n* Rye flour",
